#since the given data is cummulative sum so we add new features with daily basis continuation

india_data = data %>% filter(Country.Region=='India')

## this is cummulative data
ggplot(data=india_data, aes(x=Date, y=Confirmed)) + 
  geom_line()

## daily confirmed
india_data = india_data %>% 
  mutate(daily_cases = Confirmed-lag(Confirmed,n = 1, default = 0),
                                   daily_recovered = Recovered-lag(Recovered,default=0),
         daily_deaths = Deaths-lag(Deaths,default=0))


ggplot(data=india_data, aes(x=Date, y=daily_cases)) + 
  geom_line()

ggplot(data=india_data[india_data$daily_recovered>=0,], aes(x=Date, y=daily_recovered)) + 
  geom_line()

ggplot(data=india_data[india_data$daily_recovered>=0,], aes(x=Date, y=daily_deaths)) + 
  geom_line()

4. Construct the model using the Simple moving average, Exponential Moving Average and ARIMA to forecast the Covid19 Dataset.

#Simple moving average
library("TTR")
SMA1 <- SMA(india_data$daily_cases,n=31)
plot.ts(SMA1,ylab="SMA Daily Confirmed prediction")

#Exponential Moving Average
ema <-EMA(india_data$daily_cases,n=31)
plot.ts(ema,ylab="EMA Daily Confirmed prediction")

# ARIMA
fit <- auto.arima(india_data$daily_cases)
  
forecastedValues <- forecast(fit, 31)
  
  
plot(forecastedValues, ylab = "ARIMA Daily Confirmed prediction",
col.main = "darkgreen")
